// 03d-data-features-quality — Feature Engineering and Data Quality

The raw data sources described in the preceding sections span heterogeneous formats, naming conventions, and levels of completeness. Before any modeling can proceed, each compound must be reduced to a fixed-length numerical representation that captures the relevant chemistry while remaining compatible with standard machine learning algorithms. This section describes the feature engineering pipelines for NMR spectra and molecular fingerprints, the identifier resolution challenges that arise when linking records across databases, and the data quality issues that constrain the effective training set size.

=== NMR Feature Extraction Pipeline <nmr-feature-pipeline>

Experimental $""^1"H"$ NMR data in the NMRexp database arrive as structured peak lists rather than continuous spectra. Each entry is a list of tuples recording the multiplicity, coupling constants, integral (in hydrogen equivalents), and the high and low bounds of the chemical shift range for every resolved signal @Wang2025NMRexp. A triplet at 3.68 ppm integrating for two hydrogens with a coupling constant of 3.8 Hz, for example, is stored as `('t', ['3.8Hz'], '2H', 3.68, 3.68)`. Converting these discrete descriptors into a uniform numerical representation requires two stages: spectrum reconstruction via lineshape simulation, and domain-informed feature extraction from the reconstructed spectrum.

In the first stage, the peak list is parsed and each signal is rendered onto a 1200-point grid spanning 0--12 ppm. Singlets, doublets, triplets, and quartets are simulated as sums of Lorentzian lineshapes with Pascal's triangle intensity ratios, using the reported coupling constants to determine line separations in ppm (dividing Hz values by an assumed spectrometer frequency of 400 MHz). Higher-order multiplets such as doublets of doublets are generated by successive splitting: each existing line is split into a doublet about its center for every additional coupling constant. Unresolved multiplets, denoted "m" in the peak list, are rendered as Gaussian envelopes whose width matches the reported chemical shift range. Each Lorentzian line has a half-width at half-maximum of 0.01 ppm, chosen to be narrow enough to preserve peak identity while broad enough that the 0.01 ppm grid spacing captures the lineshape adequately. After all peaks have been rendered, the spectrum is max-normalized to the interval $[0, 1]$.

The 1200-point spectrum is too high-dimensional relative to the available training set (hundreds to low thousands of compounds), so a second stage extracts 120 domain-informed features organized into four groups.

The first group consists of 60 fine spectral bin features. The 0--12 ppm range is divided into 30 bins of 0.4 ppm width, and for each bin the mean and maximum signal intensity are recorded. These capture the overall shape of the spectrum at a resolution matched to the precision of the chemical shift data.

The second group consists of 27 chemical shift region features. Nine chemically meaningful regions of the $""^1"H"$ spectrum are defined, and for each region three quantities are computed: the integral (sum of signal, proportional to the number of protons in that environment), the fraction of the total integral attributable to that region, and the number of distinct peaks (counted as upward threshold crossings at 5% of maximum intensity). @tbl-shift-regions lists the nine regions and their chemical significance. The aromatic and olefinic regions are particularly informative for fuel applications because aromatic content correlates strongly with density and surface tension, while the alkyl regions encode chain length information relevant to viscosity @Cookson1987 @Edwards2017.

